{"questionId":"33018049","questionHtml":"<p>Show that the complex roots of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math> form a reciprocal pair.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>roots are&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>±</mo><mtext>i&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mtext>i</mtext><mo>,</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mtext>i</mtext></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>=</mo><mtext>cis </mtext><mfenced><mrow><mo>±</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><msup><mtext>,=e</mtext><mrow><mo>±</mo><mtext>i</mtext><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)<br><br></strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mtext>i</mtext><mtext>i</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mtext>i</mtext></math> &nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mtext>i</mtext></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mtext>i</mtext></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award as above for showing that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mtext>i</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mtext>i</mtext></math> &nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp; stating that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mtext>i</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mtext>i</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>i</mtext><mo>×</mo><mo>-</mo><mtext>i</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> &nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>i</mtext><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mtext>i</mtext></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1<br><br></strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>the product of roots is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1<br><br></strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p>hence the roots form a reciprocal pair&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>AG</em></strong></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><strong><em>[2 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"33018049","referenceCode":"24N.3.AHL.TZ0.2b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Show that the complex roots of x2+1=0 form a reciprocal pair.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.12—Factor and remainder theorems, sum and product of roots","Topic 1—Number and algebra","AHL 1.12—Complex numbers – Cartesian form and Argand diag"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}